<paragraph blockId="19.[92,1047,1093,1245]" pageId="19" pageNumber="144">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezzi" authorityYear="1924" box="[132,243,1093,1117]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis box="[132,243,1093,1117]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="144">E. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most northerly of the species and one of the smallest (
<quantity box="[913,1031,1093,1117]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="144" unit="mm" value="10.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="10.0">10±11 mm</quantity>
). It also has a long narrow abdomen and a broader more rounded epiphallus than other species in this study suggesting that it is not closely related to the others but because of its similar general appearance I have included it. 
<bibRefCitation author="BEZZI, M." box="[778,921,1189,1213]" pageId="19" pageNumber="144" refId="ref11358" refString="BEZZI, M., 1924, The Bombyliidae of the Ethiopian Region. (London: British Museum, Natural History), 390 pp." type="book" year="1924">Bezzi (1924)</bibRefCitation>
gave a full description and 
<bibRefCitation author="GREATHEAD, D. J." box="[278,481,1221,1245]" pageId="19" pageNumber="144" pagination="284" refId="ref11496" refString="GREATHEAD, D. J., 1967, The Bombyliidae (Diptera) of northern Ethiopia, Journal of Natural History, 1, 195 ± 284." type="journal article" year="1967">Greathead (1967)</bibRefCitation>
illustrated the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
